<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,331,1365]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,547,573]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Description.</emphasis>
Slightly encrusting habit. Specimen CNPGG-2245 is fragmented and excavating the coral rubble. The encrusting specimen’s size is 3.5 × 2.5 × 
<quantity box="[655,713,583,610]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="cm" value="1.0">1 cm</quantity>
. Surface microhispid and undulated. Oscules are scattered. Color 
<emphasis box="[151,227,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">in vivo</emphasis>
white, light-beige preserved in ethanol. The consistency is brittle, easily broken.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,331,1365]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,655,681]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Skeleton.</emphasis>
Ectosome is detachable, and the tangential skeleton shows unispicular reticulation (
<figureCitation box="[1273,1378,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1942,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1389,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-445@43.[151,1435,1389,1918]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 37. Xestospongia arenosa van Soest &amp; de Weerdt, 2001 (CNPGG-2237), skeleton and spicules: A. tangential section of the skeleton of the ectosomal region; B. transversal section of the skeleton; C. oxeas. Scale bars: A–B = 250 µm; C = 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5454454" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5454454/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 37A</figureCitation>
), enclosing meshes 150–270 µm in diameter. An isotropic reticulation conforms the choanosomal skeleton from ill-defined tracts, traversed single-spicules (
<figureCitation box="[586,689,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1942,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1389,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-445@43.[151,1435,1389,1918]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 37. Xestospongia arenosa van Soest &amp; de Weerdt, 2001 (CNPGG-2237), skeleton and spicules: A. tangential section of the skeleton of the ectosomal region; B. transversal section of the skeleton; C. oxeas. Scale bars: A–B = 250 µm; C = 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5454454" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5454454/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 37B</figureCitation>
), and rounded meshes 350–500 µm in diameter. The skeleton that goes close to the surface is confused and vague.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,331,1365]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,799,825]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Spicules.</emphasis>
Megascleres: Oxeas to styles, slightly curved, with a wide range in size (
<figureCitation box="[1133,1228,799,826]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1942,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1389,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-445@43.[151,1435,1389,1918]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 37. Xestospongia arenosa van Soest &amp; de Weerdt, 2001 (CNPGG-2237), skeleton and spicules: A. tangential section of the skeleton of the ectosomal region; B. transversal section of the skeleton; C. oxeas. Scale bars: A–B = 250 µm; C = 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5454454" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5454454/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig.37C</figureCitation>
); 250– 
<emphasis box="[1305,1347,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">375</emphasis>
(50.1)– 420/8.5– 
<emphasis box="[250,299,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">14.3</emphasis>
(3.3)–19 µm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
